t[ egin{array}{lll} rac{1}{2} & 0 & 0 \ 0 &  rac{1}{3} & 0 \ 0 & 0 &  rac{1}{5}\end{array}ight]{/tex} Explanation: {tex}\left[ egin{array}{lll} rac{1}{2} & 0 & 0 \ 0 &  rac{1}{3} & 0 \ 0 & 0 &  rac{1}{5}\end{array}ight]{/tex} 1 Questions number 19 and 20 are Assertion and Reason based questions. Two statements are given, one labelled Assertion (A) and the other labelled Reason {tex}(R){/tex} . Select the correct answer from the codes (A), (B), (C) and (D) as given below. Both Assertion (A) and Reason (R) are true and Reason (R) is the correct explanation of the Assertion (A). Both Assertion (A) and Reason (R) are true, but Reason (R) is not the correct explanation of the Assertion (A). Assertion (A) is true, but Reason (R) is false. Assertion (A) is false, but Reason (R) is true. 19. Assertion (A): Every scalar matrix is a diagonal matrix. Reason ( {tex}R{/tex} ): In a diagonal matrix, all the diagonal elements are 0. a. Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. b. Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A. c. A is true but R is false. d. A is false but R is true. Correct Answer: (c) A is true but R is false. Explanation: A is true but R is false. 1 20. Assertion (A): Projection of {tex}\overrightarrow{{a}}{/tex} on {tex}\overrightarrow{{b}}{/tex} is same as projection of {tex}\overrightarrow{{b}}{/tex} on {tex}\overrightarrow{{a}}{/tex} . Reason {tex}(R){/tex} : Angle between {tex}\overrightarrow{{a}}{/tex} and {tex}\overrightarrow{{b}}{/tex} is same as angle between {tex}\overrightarrow{{b}}{/tex} and {tex}\overrightarrow{{a}}{/tex} numerically. a. Both A and R are true and R is the correct explanation of A. b. Both A and R are true but R is not the correct explanation of A. c. A is true but R is false. d. A is false but R is true. Correct Answer: (d) A is false but R is true. Explanation: A is false but R is true. 1 Section - B This section comprises very short answer (VSA) type questions of 2 marks each. 21. Evaluate: {tex}\sec ^{2}\left(	an ^{-1}  rac{1}{2}ight)+\operatorname{cosec}^{2}\left(\cot ^{-1}  rac{1}{3}ight){/tex} Solution: {tex}\sec ^{2}\left(	an ^{-1}  rac{1}{2}ight)+\operatorname{cosec}\left(\cot ^{-1}  rac{1}{3}ight){/tex} {tex}=\left[1+	an ^{2}\left(	an ^{-1}  rac{1}{2}ight)ight]+\left[1+\cot ^{2}\left(\cot ^{-1}  rac{1}{3}ight)ight]{/tex} {tex}=\left[1+\left( rac{1}{2}ight)^{2}ight]+\left[1+\left( rac{1}{3}ight)^{2}ight]{/tex} {tex}= rac{85}{36}{/tex} 2 22. (i) If {tex}{x}={e}^{{x} / {y}}{/tex} , prove that {tex} rac{{dy}}{{dx}}= rac{\log {x}-1}{(\log {x})^{2}}{/tex} Solution: {tex}x=e^{ rac{x}{y}} \Rightarrow \log x= rac{x}{y} \Rightarrow y= rac{x}{\log x}{/tex} {tex}\Rightarrow  rac{d y}{d x}= rac{(\log x)(1)-x\left( rac{1}{x}ight)}{(\log x)^{2}}= rac{\log x-1}{(\log x)^{2}}{/tex} 2 OR (ii) Check the differentiability of {tex}{f}({x})=\left\{ egin{array}{cr}{x}^{2}+1, & 0 \leq {x} \lt 1 \ 3-{x}, & 1 \leq {x} \leq 2\end{array}ight.{/tex} at {tex}{x}=1{/tex} . Solution: LHD at {tex}x=1{/tex} {tex}=\lim \limits_{h ightarrow 0}  rac{f(1-h)-f(1)}{-h}{/tex} {tex}=\lim \limits_{h ightarrow 0}  rac{\left[(1-h)^{2}+1ight]-2}{-h}=2{/tex} RHD at {tex}x=1{/tex} {tex}=\lim \limits_{h ightarrow 0}  rac{f(1+h)-f(1)}{h}{/tex} {tex}=\lim \limits_{h ightarrow 0}  rac{[3-(1+h)]-2}{h}=-1{/tex} as {tex}{LHD} 
